<br>
Being strong or weak has nothing to do with having the right to set policy, only with the ability to set policy.  If you are referring to the fact that whoever has the ability to set the agenda does so, well, yes, this is a just a fact of life.  It applies to everything.  Is you or your boss right?  Is the parent right or the child?  Even in everquest, is the guildleader or the guildmember?  Is the uberguild or the small family guild?  In these cases it's the boss, the parent, the guildleader, the uberguild that have the final say.  Are they morally right?  Do they have any more &quot;right&quot; to set policy than the US does?  Not really, but in life we must live with the reality that the most powerful DO make the decisions.  All of us enjoy being in that position of decision making power when we are in it or when an ally is and are frustrated when someone we disagree with has the power.<br>
<br>
Whether or not we like it, it's not a precedent that the US is setting, it's simply the way the world has worked for countless eons since the beginning of time.  The lone lion may have taken down the antelope, but the 15 hyenas get to eat it if they want to.  Did Saddam have the right to take over Kuwait?  Of course most would say he did not in a moral sense have that right.  However, he did it.  The only reason it did not stand was that a bigger kid with a bigger stick decided it wouldn't.  Regardless of how immoral it was or whether or not he had the right, he'd have stayed there and occupied the country if no one more powerful had come along to kick him out.<br>
<br>
What we must hope is that the powerful make the right choices.  There is rarely if ever an objective measure of who is morally right, arguments can always go round in circles with both sides presenting their views.  Whether we like it or not, in the end, it's the one who holds more power that makes the final decision.  I don't personally like it any more than you do, but it's a reality.<br>
<br>
Fortunately for me, I happen to agree with those who are currently making the decision to remove Saddam from power.<br>
<br>
As for why the US is morally justified in doing what it is doing, I do not know of anyone that is claiming that our power is the reason we are justified.  There are many arguments for or against it, and I have yet to hear anyone claim we have the right to do so because we can.  For me it's simple.  Iraq invaded Kuwait.  Under the auspices of the UN we sent in a force to boot him out.  We did so, he surrendered, in the terms of his surrender we allowed him to keep power providing he meet certain terms and conditions of surrender.  His right to maintain power was always contingent on these, including that he prove to the world that he destroyed his WMD.  His failure to do so constitutes a loss of his right to lead Iraq.  He made his own bed, now he has to lie in it.  He was given hundreds of chances over a period of over 12 years now to comply.  Thus, his loss of a right to lead Iraq is derived from the papers which he signed at the close of the last Gulf War and his failure to keep his word.  It was always understood that failure to keep his word would result in the loss of the legitimacy of his regime, the only question is whether it would be enforced.  He tried to call Bush's bluff, but Bush wasn't bluffing.<br>
<br>
